{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Eight Elvises.jpg | image_size=250px | title=Eight Elvises | artist=Andy Warhol | year={{Start date|1963}} | type=Silkscreen on canvas | height_imperial=6.5 | width_imperial=12 | imperial_unit= ft | museum=Private collection}}
'''''Eight Elvises''''' is a 1963 [[silkscreen]] painting by American [[pop artist]] [[Andy Warhol]] of [[Elvis Presley]]. In 2008 it was sold by [[Annibale Berlingieri]] for [[USD|$]]100 million to a private buyer, making the painting the most valuable work by Andy Warhol at the time. The current owner and location of the painting, which has not been seen publicly since the 1960s, are unknown, although it is believed the buyer was the Royal Qatari family.
==Background==
''Eight Elvises'' is composed of eight identical, overlapping images of [[Elvis Presley]] in [[cowboy]] attire, silkscreened over a silver background.<ref name="MC_354freddys swag">McCarthy (2006), 354</ref><ref name=Johnson>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Andrew|title=The $100m Warhol|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/the-100m-warhol-1830661.html|accessdate=1 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=29 November 2009}}</ref> The painting was originally a portion of a {{convert|37|ft|m|abbr=out|adj=mid|long}} piece, containing sixteen copies of Elvis, that was showcased in a 1963 exhibition at the [[Ferus Gallery]] in Los Angeles. The exhibition, Warhol's second at the Ferus, contained several other pieces using the same image of Elvis, as well as a series of [[head shot]]s of [[Elizabeth Taylor]].<ref name="MC_354freddys swag" /> The images of Elvis were taken from a [[film still|publicity still]] from the movie ''[[Flaming Star]]''.<ref name=MC_363>McCarthy (2006), 363</ref> When the gallery was dismantled, the section with eight images of Elvis became a distinct piece, measuring {{convert|6+1/2|by|12|ft|cm|abbr=out}}.<ref name=Johnson /><ref>McCarthy (2006), 356</ref> While Warhol created 22 versions of the painting with two Elvises on it, known as ''Double Elvis'', only one piece titled ''Eight Elvises'' was created.<ref name=Johnson /><ref name=CNN>{{cite news|last=Lerner|first=George|title=Warhol 'Double Elvis' goes for $37 million|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/05/09/us/new-york-warhol-double-elvis/|accessdate=1 December 2013|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=10 May 2012}}</ref>
==2008 sale==
In 2008 ''Eight Elvises'' was sold by [[Annibale Berlingieri]], who had owned it for 40 years, in a private sale for [[USD|$]]100 million to an unidentified collector.<ref name=Economist>{{cite news|title=The Pop master's highs and lows|url=http://www.economist.com/node/14941229|accessdate=1 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|date=26 November 2009}}</ref> News of the sale, which was not announced publicly at the time, was broken by art writer Sarah Thornton and published in ''[[The Economist]]'' in late 2009.<ref name=Johnson /><ref name=Economist /> The deal was brokered by [[Philippe Ségalot]], a New York-based art dealer and one time head of the contemporary art department at [[Christie's]] auction house.<ref name=Economist /><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=Vogel|first=Carol|title=Auction World’s Blast of Brash|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/26/arts/design/26segalot.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=1 December 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 September 2010}}</ref> The sale made ''Eight Elvises'' one of the [[List of most expensive paintings|most expensive paintings]] ever sold, and made Warhol only the fifth artist, behind [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Gustav Klimt]], [[Jackson Pollock]], and [[Willem de Kooning]] to have a painting sold for at least $100 million.<ref name=Economist /> The current location of the painting is unknown.<ref name=Economist />
Another painting from 1963, ''[[Silver Car Crash (Double Disaster)]]'', broke the valuation record for a Warhol work set by ''Eight Elvises'' when it sold for $105 million at auction in November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andy Warhol auction record shattered|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24937683|work=BBC News|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=1 December 2013|date=14 November 2013}}</ref>
